y on their own, insurance industry administrators argued that their usage of statistical data enabled them to chart the predictable future for the aggregate. Through insurance, companies and the state thus offered consumers a means to a perfectible future in an era filled with repeated crises. Life insurance functioned as an important modernist technology within Japan and its colonies to instantiate expectations for responsibility, to reconfigure meanings of mutuality, and to normalize new social formations (such as the nuclear family) as essential to life. Life insurance thus offers an important vehicle for examining the confluence of modes of mobilizing and organizing bodies, the expropriation of financial resources, and the action of disciplining workers into a capitalist system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLife insurancezJapanxHistoryy19th century. 0aLife insurancezJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aMutualismzJapan. 4aBusiness (General). 4aHISTORY. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh  amasculinity, WWII, colonial Korea, responsibility in Japan, actuarial science, expropriating financial resources, capitalism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075184040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501773303?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501773303423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501773303/original  a978-3-11-075184-0  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles